15    /**
16    * Implementation of a time-discrete n-dimensional Brownian motion
17    * <i>W = (W<sub>1</sub>,...,W<sub>n</sub>)</i> where <i>W<sub>i</sub></i> is
18    * a Brownian motion and <i>W<sub>i</sub></i>, <i>W<sub>j</sub></i> are
19    * independent for <i>i</i> not equal <i>j</i>.
20    *
21    * For a correlated Brownian motion with see
22    * {@link net.finmath.montecarlo.CorrelatedBrownianMotion}.
23    *
24    * Here the dimension <i>n</i> is called factors since this Brownian motion is used to
25    * generate multi-dimensional multi-factor Ito processes and there one might
26    * use a different number of factors to generate Ito processes of different
27    * dimension.
28    *
29    * The quadruppel (time discretization, number of factors, number of paths, seed)
30    * defines the state of an object of this class, i.e., BrownianMotionLazyInit for which
31    * there parameters agree, generate the same random numbers.
32    *
33    * The class is immutable and thread safe. It uses lazy initialization.
34    *
35    * @author Christian Fries
36    * @version 1.6
37    */
